SIMPLE: seminary
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Seminary
<hw>Sem"i*na*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Seminaries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L.
<ets>seminarium</ets>, fr. <ets>seminarius</ets> belonging to seed, fr.
<ets>semon</ets>, <ets>seminis</ets>, seed. See <er>Seminal</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A piece of ground where seed is sown for producing
plants for transplantation; a nursery; a seed plat.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Mortimer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But if you draw them [seedling] only for the thinning of your
<qex>seminary</qex>, prick them into some empty beds.</q>
<rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, the place or original stock whence anything
is brought or produced.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Woodward.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A place of education, as a school of a high grade,
an academy, college, or university.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Seminal state.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir
T. Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Fig.: A seed bed; a source.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Harvey.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A Roman Catholic priest educated in a foreign
seminary; a seminarist.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Jer.
Taylor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seminary</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Seminary
<hw>Sem"i*na*ry</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>seminarius</ets>.]</ety> <def>Belonging to seed; seminal.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seminate</ent>⟦br⟧
